Reported [here](https://discuss.elastic.co/t/pattern-analyzer-does-not-respect-max-token-length/61975).

``` js
 POST /_analyze
    {
      "analyzer": "pattern",
      "text": "xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyy"
    }
```

Responds with:

``` js
{
  "tokens": [
    {
      "token": "xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyyy",
      "start_offset": 0,
      "end_offset": 295,
      "type": "word",
      "position": 0
    }
  ]
}
```

But `max_token_length` is documented as defaulting at `255` so this should spit out two tokens.

**Elasticsearch version**: 2.3

A multi_match query that is otherwise proper, but has an array of values for the "query" parameter will execute successfully, but only actually perform the search using the last value of the array.

Should it return an error instead?

**Steps to reproduce**:

```
# cleanup
DELETE and_match
# create index/mapping
POST and_match
{
  "settings": {
    "number_of_shards": 1,
    "number_of_replicas": 0
  },
  "mappings": {
    "type1": {
      "properties": {
        "tags": {
          "type": "string"
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
# index
POST and_match/_bulk
{ "index" : { "_type" : "type1"} }
{ "tags" : "machine"}
{ "index" : { "_type" : "type1"} }
{ "tags" : "broken"}
{ "index" : { "_type" : "type1"} }
{ "tags" : "broken machine"}
# search
POST /and_match/_search
{
    "query": {
        "multi_match": {
          "query": ["broken", "machine"], 
          "fields": ["tags"]
        }
    }
}
```

